You are Cursor AI working inside a Git repository that will contain the core 
`bus` command only. It is a tiny Go CLI called bus that acts purely as a 
subcommand dispatcher, git-style. The rule is that running “bus <command> 
…args…” must look for an executable named “bus-<command>” on PATH and execute 
it, passing through all remaining arguments unchanged. The core bus command 
must not contain any accounting logic or any knowledge of specific modules 
beyond this dispatch rule. The dispatcher must behave deterministically and be 
easy to test.

Create a Go module for the repository, place the entrypoint at cmd/bus/main.go, 
and structure the code so it is testable without relying on global os.Exit in 
the middle of logic. Do this by implementing a Run function (for example 
Run(args []string, env []string, stdin io.Reader, stdout io.Writer, stderr 
io.Writer) int) in a small internal package or in cmd/bus itself, and let 
main() call os.Exit(Run(os.Args, os.Environ(), os.Stdin, os.StdouThe dispatcher 
logic must follow these rules. If invoked with no subcommand arguments, it must 
print a short usage line to stderr and exit with code 2. If invoked with a 
subcommand name, it must resolve “bus-<name>” using exec.LookPath. If LookPath 
fails, it must print a clear error to stderr that says the subcommand is 
missing and that it expected an executable named bus-<name> to be available in 
PATH, and it must exit with code. If the subcommand is found, it must execute 
it with the remaining args, wiring stdin/stdout/stderr through unchanged, and 
inheriting the parent environment. If the subcommand exits with a non-zero 
code, bus must exit with the exact same exit code. If execution fails in a way 
that does not yield an exit code (for example, command start failure after 
LookPath, or other unexpected errors), bus must print a short “bus: …” error 
err and exit with code 1. Keep flags and features out of scope for now; this 
repo is only the dispatch behavior.

Add complete automated tests that validate all behaviors and do not depend on 
any external tools being installed. The tests must create a temporary 
directory, place it on the front of PATH for the duration of each test, and 
then provide a fake “bus-accounts” executable in that directory. Make the fake 
executable in a portable way that works on the current host OS: write a tiny Go 
program to a temp folder and compile it with “go build” into the t directory as 
“bus-accounts” (or “bus-accounts.exe” on Windows). The fake program must allow 
the tests to control its behavior via environment variables and must print 
observable output so argument passing can be verir example it can print its 
argv (excluding argv[0]) to stdout in a predictable format, and exit with a 
code read from an env var like BUS_SUBCMD_EXIT_CODE (default 0). Then write 
tests that call the Run function directly (preferred) or execute the built bus 
binary (acceptable if you keep it reliable) to prove: running with no args 
returns exit code 2 and prints usage to stderr, running “bus accounts foo bar” 
executes the fake bus-accounts and the fake sees exactly “foo bar” as args, 
stdout and stderr are passed through (at least verify stdout from the fake is 
visibning a missing subcommand returns 127 and prints the expected message, 
running a subcommand that exits 7 causes bus to exit 7, and the PATH resolution 
uses the front of PATH so your temp stub is used. Keep the tests fast and 
isolated, and avoid flaky assumptions.

Write documentation as Markdown in README.md describing the purpose of this 
repo, the subcommand naming convention, how dispatch works, what the exit codes 
mean (2 for usage, 127 for missing subcommand, pass-through for subcommand 
failures, 1 for unexpected execution errors), and a short example of how a user 
would install a module binary such as bus-accounts so that “bus accounts” 
works. Also include a brief design ratio section that explicitly says this core 
is intentionally minimal and all features live in separate repos/binaries. Add 
a short CONTRIBUTING note that running “go test ./...” should pass and that 
this repo intentionally does not inclany business logic. Ensure all new files 
are formatted, buildable, and tests pass with a clean checkout.

Add a `Makefile` at the repository root that provides a small, consistent 
developer interface for building, testing, formatting, and linting the 
bus-accounts codebase; it must include targets for building the binary (for 
example `make build` producing `bin/bus-accounts`), running the full test suite 
(`make test` running `go test ./...`), formatting (`make fmt` running `gofmt` 
over the repository), and a single convenience target (`make check`) that runs 
formatting and tests in a deterministic order, with all commands failing the 
target on error and without requiring any external tools beyond a standard Go 
toolchain and POSIX make.

Finally, implement everything in the working tree: go.mod, cmd/bus/main.go, 
any internal package files you need, tests, and README.md. Keep the code small, 
readable, and idiomatic Go, and do not add any extra features beyond what is 
described here.
